The best thing about this episode of Thresholds featuring comedian @harikondabolu is goddamn *all* of it. Every last bit. His singular ability to make us laugh about the shit that usually makes us cry is on full display here, along with his wiry curiosity, his stories of growing up in Queens, the first joke he was really proud of, and the power that comes from alienating the audience on purpose. Also, we asked for one epiphany and the man gave us four. FOUR! Welcome to your weekend of abundance.

Comic @harikondabolu preps for every stand-up performance the same way: drinking lots of water, peeing and pacing. 

“It’s the same thing over and over, and I think there’s a comfort in that,” he said. “I’ve been doing this 20 years, and I’m still absolutely a mess until I go on.”

The comedian is gearing up for the release of his latest special, “Vacation Baby,” which he will self-release on YouTube on Tuesday. Named for his son, who was born during the pandemic but conceived just before lockdown, the special’s nontraditional release is a gamble for Kondabolu, who is no stranger to betting on himself.

“It just felt like I had this major life thing happen, and I had so much to talk about from those two years of the pandemic,” he said. “And I’m just sitting on it waiting for what exactly? For a network to give me the right to say what I want to say publicly?”

Read The Times’ interview with Hari at the link in bio.

I played @tafttheatre in Cincinnati on Friday for the first time since March 11, 2020. It was my last show for 2 years. That night, I think the audience and I both knew this might be it for a while & I believe we both gave it our all. It was magical & I listened to the iPhone recording of that show for 2 years as I waited for some sense of normalcy to return. It was a lovely last memory of being a standup comic. It was a privilege to be back & I am forever grateful, Cincinnati.

Hari Kondabolu is a comedian, writer and podcaster based in Brooklyn. The NY Times called him “one of the most exciting political comics in stand-up today” and described his 2018 Netflix special Warn Your Relatives as “an incisively funny and formally adventurous hour that reveals a comic in command of his powers.” The special was named on many “Best of” lists, including for Time, Paste Magazine, Cosmopolitan, E! Online, and Mashable. He was also named one of 2018’s “Comics To Watch” by Variety. Hari currently hosts the new Netflix food competition series Snack vs Chef along with Megan Stalter.

In 2017, his truTV documentary The Problem with Apu was released to critical acclaim and spurred a global conversation about race and representation. The Nation called it “a devastating critique of the ultimate comedic sacred cow: The Simpsons.” It is now used in high school, college and grad school curriculums around the US.

Hari has also released two comedy albums, Waiting for 2042 & Mainstream American Comic with legendary indie rock label Kill Rock Stars. Additionally, he has performed on such shows as Conan, Jimmy Kimmel Live, and The Late Show with David Letterman among many others. He is also a former writer & correspondent on the much loved, Chris Rock produced FX show Totally Biased with W. Kamau Bell.

In the delicious episode of #YourMamasKitchen with @harikondabolu, the comedian describes how he used to shun his mom’s cooking as a kid but grew to  love it as he got older, wiser and more grateful for his mother’s gifts in the kitchen. I felt like I got to know his mother, Uma in this episode and she is a remarkable woman.  Wise and funny and a great cook.  Hari shared her recipe for peanut chutney served with breakfast cakes called Idli and now you can enjoy it too.  Listen to the full episode whenever you find your podcasts. Link in bio.

As one of Live Wire’s very favorite guests, comedian Hari Kondabolu might be the smartest person you laugh at this year. Before becoming a regular on public radio and appearing on NPR’s Wait Wait...Don’t Tell Me and Midday on WNYC, Hari earned a Masters in Human Rights from the London School of Economics and worked as an immigrant rights organizer in Seattle. Because of his educational background, his comedy is a complex blend of social commentary, honest personal experience, and trenchant political wit. He has released two comedy albums and has performed on Conan, Jimmy Kimmel Live, and The Late Show with David Letterman among others.. His 2018 Netflix special, Warn Your Relatives, made many “Best of” lists, and his critically-acclaimed documentary, The Problem with Apu, has been making waves since 2017. He also co-hosts the podcast The Untitled Kondabolu Brothers Podcast with his younger brother.

One of my all-time favorite actors whose performance as Det Frank Pembleton in Homicide: Life on the Street is amongst the best acting I’ve ever seen. And honestly, he was good in everything. What a loss.

Every wonderful thing people said about @kennydeforest is true. I found this wonderful exchange we had years ago about my documentary “The Problem with Apu.” He sent it during a time when I was getting a lot of hate mail & death threats. It’s like he knew I needed the love, especially when a lot of my peers (esp the white ones) turned on me. He was thoughtful & kind & clearly cared a lot about justice & fairness. 

We lost a good human, everyone. It’s a sad day.
